[thinking] It looks like we might need to make some changes to our error handling process. Specifically, I think we should handle `LinkageError` in our tests, similar to how we manage `statusLine`. Since tests run under Native Image by default, adding catches for `LinkageError` before general `Error` will make sense. Otherwise, current catch statements will only address unsupported features, which could lead to other init errors from Groovy not being caught. I should ensure the test adheres to the existing patterns.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Evaluating error handling**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m noticing that the existing pattern doesn’t use assertThrows. Instead, it catches NoClassDefFoundError manually and checks if it’s a native failure. I think we should reflect that to help distinguish between cases. For the missing class, NoClassDefFoundError could point to an expected class that's missing or an initialization failure. It feels like I should edit this manual check. Also, does this class need any running? I'll figure that out!
